      <section xml:id="Jan-27">
        <title>Jan. 27: Set Operations, Relations, and Equivalence Relations</title>
        
        <introduction>
          
          <assemblage>
            <title>Motivating Questions</title>
            <p>
            <statement>
            After wrapping up set theory, here are some questions we'll consider.
            <ol>
              <li>What is a relation?</li>
              <li>What properties might a relation have?</li>
              <li>What is an equivalence relation, and what are some examples?</li>
            </ol>
            </statement>
            </p>
            
          </assemblage>
          
          
            
            
           
          </introduction>
          
          <subsection>
            <title>Outline</title>
            
            <subsubsection>
              <title>Set Operations</title>
              
              <assemblage>
                <title>Cardinality</title>
                <p>
                  <statement>
                   The number of elements in a set <m>A</m> is called its <term>cardinality</term>, denoted <m>\card{A}</m>.
                   If <m>\card{A}</m> is a finite number, we say <m>A</m> is <term>finite</term>. Otherwise, we say <m>A</m> is infinite.
                  </statement>
                </p>
              </assemblage>
              
              <activity>
                <statement>
                  <p>
                    Find the cardinality of the following sets.
                  </p>
                  <ol>
                    <li><m>A=\set{20, 21, \ldots, 35}</m></li>
                    <li><m>T = \set{1,\set{2,3},\set{4},\emptyset}</m></li>
                    <li><m>X = \set{2, 4, 6, 8, 6, 4, 2}</m></li>
                    <li><m>\pow(\set{1,\triangle,\set{5}})</m></li>
                  </ol>
                </statement>
                </activity>
              
              <assemblage>
                <title>Union and Intersection</title>
                <p>
                  <statement>
                    Let <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> be sets.
                    The <term>union</term> of <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>, denoted <m>A\cup B</m>, is the set containing all elements <m>x</m> which are in <m>A</m> or <m>B</m> (or both).
                    The intersection <m>A\cap B</m> is the set of all elements of <m>x</m> in both <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>.
                  </statement>
                </p>
              </assemblage>
              
              <p permid="SNP">
                Often when dealing with sets,
                we will have some understanding as to what <q>everything</q> is.
                Perhaps we are only concerned with natural numbers.
                In this case we would say that our
                <term>universe</term> is <m>\N</m>.
                <idx><h>universe set</h></idx>
                Sometimes we denote this universe by <m>\U</m>.
                Given this context,
                we might wish to speak of all the elements which are
                <em>not</em> in a particular set.
                We say <m>B</m> is the <term>complement</term>
                    <idx><h>complement of a set</h></idx>
                of <m>A</m>, and write,
                <me permid="Czy">
                  B = \bar A
                </me>
                when <m>B</m> contains every element not contained in <m>A</m>.
                So, if our universe is <m>\{1, 2,\ldots, 9, 10\}</m>,
                and <m>A = \{2, 3, 5, 7\}</m>,
                then <m>\bar A = \{1, 4, 6, 8, 9,10\}</m>.
              </p>
              
              <p permid="yUY">
                Of course we can perform more than one operation at a time.
                For example, consider
                <me permid="iGH">
                  A \cap \bar B
                </me>.
              </p>
          
              <p permid="fch">
                This is the set of all elements which are both elements of <m>A</m> and not elements of <m>B</m>.
                What have we done?
                We've started with <m>A</m> and removed all of the elements which were in <m>B</m>.
                Another way to write this is the
                <term>set difference</term>:
                    <idx><h>set</h><h>difference</h></idx>
                    <idx><h>difference of sets</h></idx>
                <me permid="ONQ">
                  A \cap \bar B = A \setminus B
                </me>.
              </p>
              
              <exploration>
                <statement>
                  <p>
                    Let <m>A = \set{2,3,4,5}</m> and <m>B=\set{1,5}</m> be subsets of the universe <m>\mathcal{U} = \set{1,2,3,4,5}</m>.
                    List the elements of the following sets.
                  </p>
                  <ol>
                    <li><m>{\bar A}</m></li>
                    <li><m>{\bar B}</m></li>
                    <li><m>A\cup B</m></li>
                    <li><m>A\cap B</m></li>
                    <li><m>A\setminus B</m></li>
                    <li><m>B\setminus A</m></li>
                  </ol>
                </statement>
                </exploration>
                
            </subsubsection>
            
            
