      <section xml:id="Jan-29">
        <title>Jan. 29: Relations</title>
        
        <introduction>
          
          <assemblage>
            <title>Motivating Questions</title>
            <p>
            <statement>
            Here are some questions we'll consider.
            <ol>
              <li>What are some more (non)examples of equivalence relations?</li>
              <li>How do we verify whether a given relation is an equivalence relation or not?</li>
              <li>What are partitions? What do they have to do with equivalence relations?</li>
            </ol>
            </statement>
            </p>
            
          </assemblage>

          
            
            
           
          </introduction>
          
          <subsection>
            <title>Outline</title>
            
            <p>
            Today's material is not in the book. For more on relations, feel free to consult Sundstrom's <url href="https://www.tedsundstrom.com/mathematical-reasoning-3"><emph>Mathematical Reasoning</emph></url> book.
            </p>
            
            <subsubsection>
              <title>Cartesian Products</title>
              
              <assemblage>
                <title>Cartesian Product</title>
                <p>
                  <statement>
                   The last way we'll combine sets <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> involves making ordered pairs.
                   We say the <term>Cartesian product</term> of <m>A</m> with <m>B</m> is the set of all ordered pairs <m>(a,b)</m> in which <m>a\in A</m> and <m>b\in B</m>.
                   That is, <m>A \times B = \{(a,b) \st a \in A \wedge b \in B\}</m>.
                  </statement>
                </p>
              </assemblage>
              
              <activity>
                <statement>
                  <p>
                    Let <m>A = \set{\square,\triangle,\bigcirc}</m> and <m>B=\set{2,3}</m>.
                    List the elements of either <m>A\times B</m> or <m>B\times A</m> (your choice). Do the two products have the same elements? Explain. Then calculate <m>\card{A\times A}</m>.
                  </p>
                </statement>
                </activity>
          
          </subsubsection>
          
          <subsubsection>
            <title>Relations</title>
          
          
          
          <p>
          Today's material is not in our book. For more on relations, feel free to consult Sundstrom's <url href="https://www.tedsundstrom.com/mathematical-reasoning-3"><emph>Mathematical Reasoning</emph></url> book.
          </p>
          
          <assemblage>
            <title>Relations</title>
            <p>
              <statement>
                Let <m>S,T</m> be sets.
                A <term>relation</term> <m>\mathcal{R}</m> on <m>S</m> and <m>T</m> is a subset of <m>S\times T</m>. That is, <m>\mathcal{R}\subseteq S\times T</m>.
                We write <m>(s,t)\in \mathcal{R}</m> to say that <m>s</m> is related to <m>t</m> under the relation.
                We sometimes write <m>s \mathcal{R} t</m>.
                
                The <term>relation class</term> of <m>x\in S</m> is the set of everything related to <m>x</m> from <m>T</m>: <m>[x] = \setof{y\in T}{x\mathcal{R}y}</m>.
              </statement>
            </p>
          </assemblage>
          
          <exploration xml:id="expl-relation">
            <statement>
              <p>
                Define a relation <m>\mathcal{D}</m> on <m>\Z</m> by <m>(m,n)\in \mathcal{D}</m> iff <m>m</m> divides <m>n</m>. Calculate:
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li><m>[6]</m></li>
                <li><m>[10]</m></li>
                <li><m>[30]</m></li>
                <li><m>[60]</m></li>
                <li><m>[6]\cap[10]</m></li>
              </ol>
            </statement>
            </exploration>
            
            
            <assemblage>
              <title>Properties of Relations</title>
              <p>
                <statement>
                  Let <m>X</m> be a set and <m>\sim</m> a relation on <m>X</m>, so that if <m>x,y\in X</m> and <m>(x,y)\in \sim</m>, we may write the more conventional <m>x\sim y</m>.
                  
                  <ol>
                    <li>We say that <m>\sim</m> is <term>reflexive</term> if whenever <m>x\in X</m>, <m>x\sim x</m>.</li>
                    <li>We say that <m>\sim</m> is <term>symmetric</term> if whenever <m>x,y\in X</m> and <m>x\sim y</m>, then <m>y\sim x</m>.</li>
                    <li>We say that <m>\sim</m> is <term>transitive</term> if whenever <m>x,y,z\in X</m> such that <m>x\sim y</m> and <m>y\sim z</m>, then <m>x\sim z</m>.
                    </li>
                  </ol>
                </statement>
              </p>
            </assemblage>
            
            <exploration>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Is the relation from <xref ref="expl-relation" /> reflexive? Symmetric? Transitive?
                </p>
              </statement>
              </exploration>
              
              <exploration>
                <statement>
                  <p>
                    Consider the relation <m>\mathcal{B}</m> defined on the set of all people by <m>(x,y)\in \mathcal{B}</m> iff <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> have the same birthday. Is this relation reflexive? Symmetric? Transitive?
                  </p>
                </statement>
                </exploration> 
                
                <exploration>
                  <statement>
                    <p>
                      Let <m>X = \set{1,2,3,4,5}</m>.
                    </p>
                    <ol>
                      <li>Define a relation <m>\mathcal{R}</m> on <m>X</m> that is reflexive, but not symmetric or transitive.</li>
                      <li>Define a relation <m>\mathcal{S}</m> on <m>X</m> that is symmetric, but not reflexive or transitive.</li>
                      <li>Define a relation <m>\mathcal{T}</m> on <m>X</m> that is transitive, but not symmetric or reflexive.</li>
                    </ol>
                  </statement>
                  </exploration>
                  
                  
                  <assemblage>
                    <title>Equivalence Relation</title>
                    <p>
                      <statement>
                        A relation that is reflexive, symmetric, and transitive is known as a <term>equivalence relation</term>.
                      </statement>
                    </p>
                  </assemblage>
                  
                  <activity>
                    <statement>
                      <p>
                        Which of the relations we've seen so far are equivalence relations?
                        Can you think of any others?
                      </p>
                    </statement>
                    </activity>
                    
                    
                    <example>
                      <statement>
                        <p>
                          Consider the relation <m>\mathcal{P}</m> on <m>\mathbb{Z}</m>.
                          Then <m>\mathcal{P}</m> is an equivalence relation.
                        </p>
                      </statement>
                    </example>
          
          </subsubsection>
            
            
            
                
                
            
            
            
            
           
            
            
            
            <subsubsection>
              <title>Partitions</title>
              
              <assemblage>
                <title>Partitions</title>
                <p>
                  <statement>
                    Let <m>X</m> be a set.
                    Then a partition <m>\mathfrak{P}</m> of <m>X</m> is a subsets of <m>\pow(X)</m> satisfying:
                    <ol>
                      <li>Each element of <m>\mathfrak{P}</m> is nonempty</li>
                      <li>If <m>x\in X</m>, then there is some <m>S\in \mathfrak{P}</m> with <m>x\in S</m></li>
                      <li>The family <m>\mathfrak{P}</m> is <term>pairwise disjoint</term>: if <m>S,T\in \mathfrak{P}</m>, then <m>S\cap T = \emptyset</m></li>
                    </ol>
                  </statement>
                </p>
              </assemblage>
              
              <exploration>
                <statement>
                  <p>
                    Let <m>U</m> denote the set of all cities in the United States, and let <m>I</m> denote the set of all states in the United States.
                    For each state <m>i</m>, let <m>T_i</m> denote the set of all cities within the state <m>i</m>.
                    Let <m>\mathcal{F} = \setof{T_i}{i\in I}</m> and let <m>\sim</m> denote the relation associated to <m>\mathcal{F}</m>.
                  </p>
                  <ol>
                    <li>Is <m>\sim</m> reflexive?</li>
                    <li>Is <m>\sim</m> symmetric?</li>
                    <li>Is <m>\sim</m> transitive?</li>
                    <li>Is <m>\mathcal{F}</m> a partition of <m>U</m>?</li>
                  </ol>
                </statement>
                </exploration>
            
            
            </subsubsection>
            
            
            
          </subsection>
          
