      <chapter xml:id="Week-04">
        <title>Week 4: Feb. 1-5</title>
        
        <introduction>
          <p>
              This week, we are all about <term>functions</term>. The notion of function is a foundational idea in all fields of mathematics and related disciplines, from calculus to abstract algebra and everywhere in between, including the discrete ideas we'll explore this semester. So, this week we get a brief overview of what functions (defined more abstractly) are, as well as some of the properties they might have. Don't forget that the first reading reflection is due on Monday (Feb 1), and we'll discuss the reading in class on Wednesday.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        
        <section xml:id="Feb-01">
          <title>Feb. 1: Functions</title>
          
          <introduction>
          
          
            
            <assemblage>
              <title>Motivating Questions</title>
              <p>
              <statement>
              Here are some questions we'll consider.
              <ol>
                <li>What is a function?</li>
                <li>What are some of the key terms needed for clearly describing functions?</li>
                <li>What are some examples of functions, and how do we calculate domain, codomain, image, range, etc?</li>
              </ol>
              </statement>
              </p>
              
            </assemblage>
            
            
              
              
             
            </introduction>
            
            <subsection>
              <title>Outline</title>
              
              <p>
              Today's material comes from <url href="http://discrete.openmathbooks.org/dmoi3/sec_intro-functions.html">Section 0.4</url> of the book. You're encouraged to read it before coming to class.
              </p>
              
              <subsubsection>
                <title>Finishing Relations</title>
                
                
                  
                  <assemblage>
                    <title>Equivalence Relation</title>
                    <p>
                      <statement>
                        A relation that is reflexive, symmetric, and transitive is known as a <term>equivalence relation</term>.
                      </statement>
                    </p>
                  </assemblage>
                  
                  <exploration>
                    <statement>
                      <p>
                        Verify that the following are equivalence relations on the indicated sets.
                      </p>
                      <ol>
                        <li>The relation <m>\mathcal{M}</m> on <m>\Z</m> defined by <m>(m,n)\in \mathcal{M}</m> iff <m>m-n</m> is evenly divisible by 3.</li>
                        <li>The relation <m>\mathcal{Q}</m> on <m>\R</m> defined by <m>(s,t)\in \mathcal{Q}</m> iff <m>s-t</m> is rational.</li>
                        <li>Let <m>X = \set{1,\ldots, 10}</m>, <m>X_n = \set{2n-1,2n}</m> for <m>n=1,2,\ldots, 5</m>. Convince yourself that 
                        <me>X = X_1 \cup X_2 \cup \cdots \cup X_5.</me> 
                        Then, define a relation <m>\mathcal{R}</m> on <m>X</m> by <m>(x,y)\in \mathcal{R}</m> iff there exists <m>i\in \set{1,2,\ldots,5}</m> for which <m>x,y\in X_i</m>.</li>
                      </ol>
                    </statement>
                    </exploration>
              
              </subsubsection>
              
              
              <subsubsection>
                <title>The definition of a function</title>
                
                <p>
                  The definition of a function we supply here is slightly different than the <url href="http://discrete.openmathbooks.org/dmoi3/sec_intro-functions.html#sKa">definition given in the book</url>, as we have the language of relations that our book does not develop.
                </p>
                
                <definition>
                  <statement>
                    <p>
                      Let <m>X,Y</m> be nonempty sets.
                      A <term>function</term> (or <term>map</term>, or <term>mapping</term>) is a relation <m>f</m> on <m>X\times Y</m> in which each element <m>x\in X</m> is related to exactly one element <m>y\in Y</m>. We write <m>y = f(x)</m> and <m>f : X\to Y</m>. We say that <m>X</m> is the <term>domain</term> of <m>f</m>, <m>Y</m> is the <term>codomain</term> of <m>f</m>, <m>y</m> is the <term>image</term> of <m>x</m> under <m>f</m>, and the set <m>\ran(f) = \setof{y\in Y}{\exists x\in X, y=f(x)}</m> is the <term>range</term> of <m>f</m>.
                    </p>
                  </statement>
                </definition>
                
                <p>
                  Wow, that's a lot! Let's spend some time exploring this, first with an example.
                </p>
                
                <example xml:id="example-functiondef">
                  <statement>
                    <p>
                      Consider the following relations. Are they functions? Why or why not?
                    </p>
                    <ol>
                      <li><m>X=\set{0,1,5}, Y = \set{\clubsuit, \spadesuit, \diamondsuit, \heartsuit}</m>, <m>f_1 = \set{(1,\clubsuit), (0, \heartsuit), (5,\heartsuit)}</m></li>
                      <li><m>X=\set{0,1,5}, Y = \set{\clubsuit, \spadesuit, \diamondsuit, \heartsuit}</m>, <m>f_2 = \set{(1,\clubsuit), (0, \heartsuit), (0,\diamondsuit)}</m></li>
                      <li><m>X = \set{-3,-2,-1,0,1,2,3}</m>, <m>Y = \set{0,1,2,\ldots,9}</m>, <m>f_3 = \setof{(x,x^2)}{x\in X}</m></li>
                    </ol>
                  </statement>
                </example>
                
                
                
              
              
              
              </subsubsection>
              
              <subsubsection>
                <title>Representations of Functions</title>
                
                <p>
                  <em>Definining</em> a function requires three elements: a domain, a codomain, and an assignment of each member of the domain to a unique member of the codomain.
                  As your experience suggests, there are several ways to <em>represent</em> that assignment, such as via a <q>rule</q> (e.g., those defined by algebraic expressions, though not all algebraic expressions define functions); via a graphical relationship; via a table, or in words (e.g., the birthday function).
                </p>
                
                <p>
                  In this class, our domains and codomains will generally be discrete sets, such as <m>\N</m> or <m>\Z</m>, and very often they will be <em>finite sets</em>. This allows us to be more explicit about the assignments we make.
                </p>
                
                <example>
                  <statement>
                    <p>
                      Let's represent the functions described in <xref ref="example-functiondef" /> in as many ways as possible.
                    </p>
                  </statement>
                </example>
                
                <exploration>
                  <statement>
                    <p>
                      Which of the arrow diagrams given represent functions <m>A\to B</m>, with <m>A = \set{1,2,3,4}</m> and <m>B = \set{a,b,c}</m>? Explain. For those that are functions, determine the range of the function.
                    </p>
                    
                    <image xml:id="images-arrow-diagrams" width="80%" source="./images/arrow-diagrams.png" />
                  </statement>
                  </exploration>
                
              </subsubsection>
              
              
              
              
              
            </subsection>
            
