        <section xml:id="Feb-05">
          <title>Feb. 5: Functions</title>
          
          
          <introduction>
            
            <assemblage>
              <title>Motivating Questions</title>
              <p>
              <statement>
              Here are some questions we'll consider.
              <ol>
                <li>What is the image of an element/set under a function?</li>
                <li>What is the complete inverse image of an element in the codomain of a function?</li>
                <li>What is the inverse image of the subset of the codomain of a function?</li>
              </ol>
              </statement>
              </p>
              
            </assemblage>
            
            
              
              
             
            </introduction>
            
            <subsection>
              <title>Outline</title>
              
              <p>
              Today's material comes from the last part of <url href="http://discrete.openmathbooks.org/dmoi3/sec_intro-functions.html">Section 0.4</url> of the book. You're encouraged to read it before coming to class.
              </p>
              
              <subsection>
                <title>More on Injections, Surjections, and Bijections</title>
              <exploration xml:id="expl-fcn-injsurjbij">
                <statement>
                  <p>
                    Consider the functions below. Are they injective, surjective, neither, or bijective? Explain.
                  </p>
                  <ol>
                    <li><m>f: \N\to \N</m> given by the rule <m>f(n) = 2n</m>.</li>
                    <li><m>f: \N\to \set{0,2,4,6,\ldots}</m> given by the rule <m>f(n) = 2n</m>.</li>
                    <li><m>f: \set{1,2,3,4,5}\to \set{1,2,3,4}</m> given by the <term>two-line notation</term>
                    <me permid="vjh">
                      f = \begin{pmatrix}1 \amp 2 \amp 3 \amp 4 \amp 5 \\ 2 \amp 1 \amp 3 \amp 1\amp 4 \end{pmatrix},
                    </me>
                    where the number in the first row is understood to map to the number below it.
                    </li>
                    <li>The birthday function described in <xref ref="expl-birthday-function" />.</li>
                    <li>The sum of divisors function described in <xref ref="expl-sum-of-divisors-function"  />.</li>
                    <li>The function <m>f : \N\to\Z</m> given by
                    <me>
                      f(n) = \begin{cases} n/2 \amp \text{ if } n \text{ is even} \\ -(n+1)/2 \amp \text{ if } n \text{ is odd}\end{cases}.
                    </me></li>
                  </ol>
                </statement>
                </exploration>
                
                <exploration xml:id="expl-first-counting">
                  <title>A very discrete math question</title>
                  <statement>
                    <p>
                      Using the two-line notation described above, write out all functions <m>f: \set{1,2,3}\to \set{a,b}</m>.
                    </p>
                    <ol>
                      <li>How many such functions are there?</li>
                      <li>How many are injective?</li>
                      <li>How many are surjective?</li>
                      <li>How many are bijective?</li>
                    </ol>
                  </statement>
                  </exploration>
                  
              </subsection>
              
              <subsubsection>
                <title>Recursive Definitions of Functions</title>
                
                <p>
                  We've so far seen that we can define functions by listing ordered pairs, giving rules, drawing arrow diagrams, and the like. Another important method for defining functions (especially in computer science) is with a <term>recursive definition</term>.
                </p>
                
                <p permid="DSZ">
                  Recursively defined functions are often easier to create from a
                  <q>real world</q> problem,
                  because they describe how the values of the functions are changing.
                  However, this comes with a price.
                  It is harder to calculate the image of a single input,
                  since you need to know the images of other (previous) elements in the domain.
                </p>
            
                <assemblage permid="aNA">
                  <title>Recursively Defined Functions</title>
                    <idx><h>recursively defined function</h></idx>
            
                  <p permid="RmK">
                    <idx><h>initial condition</h><h>for a function</h></idx>
                    <idx><h>recurrence relation</h><h>for a function</h></idx>
                    For a function <m>f:\N \to \N</m>,
                    a <term>recursive definition</term>
                    consists of an <term>initial condition</term>
                    together with a <term>recurrence relation</term>.
                    The initial condition is the explicitly given value of <m>f(0)</m>.
                    The recurrence relation is a formula for <m>f(n+1)</m> in terms for <m>f(n)</m>
                    (and possibly <m>n</m> itself).
                  </p>
                </assemblage>
                
                <exploration>
                  <statement>
                    <p>
                      Consider the recurrence <m>f : \N\to\N</m> given by <m>f(n+1) = 3f(n)</m>. Note that this is not enough to define a function since we don't have an initial condition. For each initial condition below, find the value of <m>f(4)</m>.
                    </p>
                    <ol>
                      <li><m>f(0)=0</m></li>
                      <li><m>f(0)=1</m></li>
                      <li><m>f(0)=2</m></li>
                      <li><m>f(0)=100</m></li>
                    </ol>
                  </statement>
                  </exploration>
              
              </subsubsection>
              
              
              <subsubsection>
                <title>Image</title>
                
                <p>
                  Let <m>f : X\to Y</m> be a function. The <term>image of <m>x\in X</m> under <m>f</m></term> is the value <m>y\in Y</m> for which <m>f(x) = y</m>.
                  This extends to entire subsets of the domain. Given <m>A\subseteq X</m>, the <term>image of <m>A</m> under <m>f</m></term> is the set 
                  <me>
                    f(A) = \setof{f(x)}{x\in A}.
                  </me>
                </p>
                
                <exploration xml:id="expl-image-of-set">
                  <statement>
                    <p>
                      Consider the function <m>f : \N\times\N \to \N</m> given by <m>f((a,b)) = a+b</m>.
                      Given <m>A = \setof{(a,b)\in \N\times\N}{a,b\le 10}</m>, find (with justification) <m>f(A)</m>.
                    </p>
                  </statement>
                  </exploration>
                  
                  <example>
                    <statement>
                      <p>
                        Suppose <m>f : X\to Y</m> and <m>A,B\subseteq X</m>. Is it true that <m>f(A\cup B) = f(A)\cup f(B)</m>?
                      </p>
                    </statement>
                  </example>
              
              </subsubsection>
              
              <subsubsection>
                <title>Inverse Images (Preimages)</title>
              
                <p>
                  If images tell us where functions send elements and sets of the codomain, then <term>inverse images</term> (sometimes called <em>preimages</em>) describe which objects in the domain get sent to particular objects (elements, subsets) of the codomain. <aside>I differ from our book in preferring the term <q>preimage</q>; the inverse image of sets and elements in the codomain can be calculated even for functions which do not have inverses, and I find the double meaning of the word <q>inverse</q> annoying.</aside>
                </p>
                
                <p>
                  Given a subset <m>B\subseteq Y</m>, the <term>inverse image of <m>B</m> under <m>f</m></term> the set 
                  <me>
                    f^{-1}(B) = \setof{x\in X}{f(x)\in B}.
                  </me>
                  If <m>B = \set{y}</m> for some <m>y\in Y</m>, we often write <m>f^{-1}(\set{y})</m> as <m>f^{-1}(y)</m>; it is the <term>complete inverse image of <m>y</m> under <m>f</m></term> (but again, <m>f^{-1}</m> need not be a well-defined function).
                </p>
                
                
                <exploration>
                  <statement>
                    <p>
                      Consider again the function from <xref ref="expl-image-of-set" />.
                    </p>
                    <ol>
                      <li>Find <m>f^{-1}(3)</m> and <m>f^{-1}(\set{0,1,2,3})</m>.</li>
                      <li>Give geometric descriptions of <m>f^{-1}(n)</m> and <m>f^{-1}(\set{0,1,2,\ldots,n})</m> for any <m>n\ge 1</m>.</li>
                      <li>Calculate <m>|f^{-1}(8)</m> and <m>|f^{-1}(\set{0,1,\ldots,8})</m>.</li>
                    </ol>
                  </statement>
                  </exploration>
                
                
                <question>
                  <statement>
                    <p>
                      Suppose <m>f : X\to Y</m> is a function and <m>1\in Y</m>. What can you say about <m>f^{-1}(1)</m> if you that:
                    </p>
                    <ol>
                      <li><m>f</m> is injective? Explain.</li>
                      <li><m>f</m> is surjective? Explain.</li>
                      <li><m>f</m> is bijective? Explain.</li>
                    </ol>
                  </statement>
                </question>
                
                <assemblage>
                  <title>Challenge</title>
                  <p>
                  <statement>
                  Let <m>f: X\to Y</m> be a function with <m>A\subseteq X</m> and <m>B\subseteq Y</m>.
                  <ol>
                    <li>Is <m>f^{-1}(f(A))=A</m>? Always? Sometimes? Never? Explain.</li>
                    <li>Is <m>f(f^{-1}(B)) = B</m>? Always? Sometimes? Never? Explain.</li>
                    <li>If one or both of the above do not always hold, is there something else you can say? Will equality always hold for particular types of functions? Is there some other relationship other than equality that would always hold? Explore.</li>
                  </ol>
                  As you consider the statements above, you may want to build one or two representative examples to test. But be careful! If your examples are too similar, you may be led down an erroneous path.
                  </statement>
                  </p>
                  
                </assemblage>
                
                
              </subsubsection>
              
              
              
              
            </subsection>
            
