        <section xml:id="Mar-10">
          <title>Mar. 10: Arithmetic and Geometric Sequences</title>
          
                      <introduction>

<assemblage>
  <title>Motivating Questions</title>
  <p>
  <statement>
	Here are some questions we'll consider.
	<ol>
	  <li>What are arithmetic and geometric sequences?</li>
	  <li>How can we use the well-understood structure of arithmetic and geometric sequences to find closed forms and sum the first <m>n</m> terms?</li>
	  <li>How can sequences of partial sums allow us to sum sequences which are neither geometric nor arithmetic?</li>
	</ol>
  </statement>
  </p>
  
</assemblage>


  
  
 
</introduction>

<subsection>
  <title>Outline</title>
  
  <p>
	Today's material comes from <url href="http://discrete.openmathbooks.org/dmoi3/sec_seq-arithgeom.html">Section 2.2</url> of the book. You're encouraged to read it before coming to class.
  </p>
  
  
  <subsubsection>
    <title>Arithmetic and Geometric Sequences</title>
    
    <exploration>
						    <statement>
						        <p>
						            Let's do the <url href="./Activity07-DotsToSequences.pdf">dots activity</url>.
						        </p>
						    </statement>
						    <solution>
						        <url href="./Activity07-DotsToSequences-solutions.pdf">Solutions here</url>
						    </solution>

						</exploration>
        
      <assemblage permid="KlB">
    <title>Arithmetic Sequences</title>
      <idx><h>arithmetic sequence</h></idx>
      <idx><h>recursive definition</h><h>for arithmetic sequence</h></idx>
      <idx><h>common difference</h></idx>
      <idx><h>closed formula</h><h>for arithmetic sequence</h></idx>
    <p permid="jcG">
      If the terms of a sequence differ by a constant,
      we say the sequence is <term>arithmetic</term>.
      If the initial term (<m>a_0</m>) of the sequence is <m>a</m> and the
      <term>common difference</term>
      is <m>d</m>, then we have,
    </p>

    <p permid="PjP">
      Recursive definition: <m>a_n = a_{n-1} + d</m> with <m>a_0 = a</m>.
    </p>

    <p permid="vqY">
      Closed formula: <m>a_n = a + dn</m>.
    </p>
  </assemblage>
  
  
  
    <example permid="kDy">
    <statement>
      <p permid="wwr">
        Find recursive definitions and closed formulas for the arithmetic sequences below.
        Assume the first term listed is <m>a_0</m>.
      </p>

      <p permid="cDA">
        <ol permid="rcE">
          <li permid="jyf"><m>2, 5, 8, 11, 14, \ldots</m>.</li>

          <li permid="PFo"><m>50, 43, 36, 29, \ldots</m>.</li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution permid="hIS">
      <p permid="pXl">
        First we should check that these sequences really are arithmetic by taking differences of successive terms.
        Doing so will reveal the common difference <m>d</m>.
      </p>

      <p permid="Weu">
        <ol permid="eOm">
          <li permid="vMx">
            <m>5-2 = 3</m>, <m>8-5 = 3</m>, etc.
            To get from each term to the next,
            we add three, so <m>d = 3</m>.
            The recursive definition is therefore <m>a_n = a_{n-1} + 3</m> with <m>a_0 = 2</m>.
            The closed formula is <m>a_n = 2 + 3n</m>.
          </li>

          <li permid="bTG">
            <p permid="Fgj">
              Here the common difference is <m>-7</m>,
              since we add <m>-7</m> to 50 to get 43, and so on.
              Thus we have a recursive definition of
              <m>a_n = a_{n-1} - 7</m> with <m>a_0 = 50</m>.
              The closed formula is <m>a_n = 50 - 7n</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>
  
    <assemblage permid="qsK">
    <title>Geometric Sequences</title>
    <idx><h>geometric sequence</h></idx>
    <idx><h>common ratio</h></idx>
    <idx><h>recursive definition</h><h>for geometric sequence</h></idx>
    <idx><h>closed formula</h><h>for geometric sequence</h></idx>
    <p permid="byh">
      A sequence is called <term>geometric</term>
      if the ratio between successive terms is constant.
      Suppose the initial term <m>a_0</m> is <m>a</m> and the
      <term>common ratio</term> is <m>r</m>.
      Then we have,
    </p>

    <p permid="HFq">
      Recursive definition: <m>a_n = ra_{n-1}</m> with <m>a_0 = a</m>.
    </p>

    <p permid="nMz">
      Closed formula: <m>a_n = a\cdot r^{n}</m>.
    </p>
  </assemblage>

  <example permid="QKH">
    <statement>
      <p permid="IKJ">
        Find the recursive and closed formula for the geometric sequences below.
        Again, the first term listed is <m>a_0</m>.

        <ol permid="XjN">
          <li permid="IaP"><m>3, 6, 12, 24, 48, \ldots</m></li>

          <li permid="ohY"><m>27, 9, 3, 1, 1/3, \ldots</m></li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution permid="NQb">
      <p permid="ClD">
        Start by checking that these sequences really are geometric by dividing each term by its previous term.
        If this ratio really is constant,
        we will have found <m>r</m>.

        <ol permid="KVv">
          <li permid="Uph">
            <m>6/3 = 2</m>, <m>12/6 = 2</m>, <m>24/12 = 2</m>, etc.
            Yes, to get from any term to the next,
            we multiply by <m>r = 2</m>.
            So the recursive definition is <m>a_n = 2a_{n-1}</m> with <m>a_0 = 3</m>.
            The closed formula is <m>a_n = 3\cdot 2^{n}</m>.
          </li>

          <li permid="Awq">
            <p permid="lns">
              The common ratio is <m>r = 1/3</m>.
              So the sequence has recursive definition <m>a_n = \frac{1}{3}a_{n-1}</m> with
              <m>a_0 = 27</m> and closed formula <m>a_n = 27\cdot \frac{1}{3}^{n}</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>
    
    
</subsubsection>

<subsubsection>
    <title>Sums of Arithmetic and Geometric Sequences</title>
    
    <investigation xml:id="investigation-seqcandy" permid="Ewp">
        <statement>
        <p permid="lXm">
          Your neighborhood grocery store has a candy machine full of Skittles.

          <ol permid="DqW">
            <li permid="gDz">
              <p permid="RuB">
                Suppose that the candy machine currently holds exactly 650 Skittles,
                and every time someone inserts a quarter,
                exactly 7 Skittles come out of the machine.

                <ol permid="gRU">
                  <li permid="AKL">
                    <p permid="UDC">
                      How many Skittles will be left in the machine after 20 quarters have been inserted?
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li permid="MKI">
                    <p permid="xBK">
                      Will there ever be exactly zero Skittles left in the machine?
                      Explain.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </li>

            <li permid="sRR">
              <p permid="dIT">
                What if the candy machine gives 7 Skittles to the first customer who put in a quarter, 10 to the second, 13 to the third, 16 to the fourth, etc.
                How many Skittles has the machine given out after 20 quarters are put into the machine?
              </p>
            </li>

            <li permid="YZa">
              <p permid="JQc">
                Now, what if the machine gives 4 Skittles to the first customer, 7 to the second, 12 to the third, 19 to the fourth, etc.
                How many Skittles has the machine given out after 20 quarters are put into the machine?
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <ol>
                <li>510 skittles; Yes? After 93 quarters?</li>
                <li>This seems to be an arithmetic sequence: <m>s_n = 3n+4, n \ge 1</m>. We can add to get <m>\frac{(7+3\cdot 20+4)\cdot 20}{2} = 710</m> skittles given out. Since there are only 650 skittles to give away, they are all gone.</li>
                <li>This one is trickier! Notice that the terms themselves are each <m>a_n  = 3 + \sum_{k=1}^n (2k-1), n\ge 1</m>. Obviously, 20 3's is 60, so we need the sum
                <me>
                    \sum\limits_{n=1}^{20} \left(\sum\limits_{k=1}^n 2k-1\right).
                </me>
                Consider the sum <m>S_n = \sum\limits_{k=1}^n 2k-1 = 1 + 3 + 5 + \cdots + 2n-1</m>.
                Then 
                    <me>
                        2S_n = \underbrace{2n+2n+2n+\cdots+2n}_{\text{n times}} = 2n^2,
                    </me>
                    so <m>S_n = n^2</m>.
                Thus, we want to find <m>60 + \sum\limits_{n=1}^{20} n^2 = 60 + 2870 = 2930</m>.
            </li>
        </ol>

                
                </solution>

      </investigation>
      
      <p>
        Some sequences, like the triangular numbers, are neither arithmetic nor geometric.
        However, the <em>differences</em> in the terms form an arithmetic sequence, so we can think of <m>T_n</m> as the <term>sequence of partial sums</term> of the sequence <m>1, 2, 3, \ldots</m>.
    </p>
    
    <p>
        We can find the sum of an arithmetic sequence using the <term>reverse and add</term> strategy.
    </p>


    <example permid="WzT">
        <statement>
          <p permid="oRS">
            Find the sum: <m>2 + 5 + 8 + 11 + 14 + \cdots + 470</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution permid="tXk">
          <p permid="isM">
            The idea is to mimic how we found the formula for triangular numbers.
            If we add the first and last terms, we get 472.
            The second term and second-to-last term also add up to 472.
            To keep track of everything, we might express this as follows.
            Call the sum <m>S</m>.
            Then,
          </p>

          <sidebyside permid="nye">

            <tabular permid="jMA">
              <col halign="right"/>
              <col halign="center"/>
              <col halign="center"/>
              <col halign="center"/>
              <col halign="center"/>
              <col halign="center"/>
              <col halign="center"/>
              <col halign="center"/>
              <col halign="center"/>
              <col halign="center"/>
              <row>
                <cell><m>S  =</m></cell>
                <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                <cell><m>+</m></cell>
                <cell><m>5</m></cell>
                <cell><m>+</m></cell>
                <cell><m>8</m></cell>
                <cell><m>+ \cdots +</m></cell>
                <cell><m>467</m></cell>
                <cell><m>+</m></cell>
                <cell>470</cell>
              </row>
              <row bottom="minor">
                <cell><m>+ \quad S  =</m></cell>
                <cell><m>470</m></cell>
                <cell><m>+</m></cell>
                <cell><m>467</m></cell>
                <cell><m>+</m></cell>
                <cell><m>464</m></cell>
                <cell><m>+ \cdots +</m></cell>
                <cell><m>5</m></cell>
                <cell><m>+</m></cell>
                <cell>2</cell>
              </row>
              <row>
                <cell><m>2S  =</m></cell>
                <cell><m>472</m></cell>
                <cell><m>+</m></cell>
                <cell><m>472</m></cell>
                <cell><m>+</m></cell>
                <cell><m>472</m></cell>
                <cell><m>+ \cdots +</m></cell>
                <cell><m>472</m></cell>
                <cell><m>+</m></cell>
                <cell><m>472</m></cell>
              </row>
            </tabular>

          </sidebyside>

          <p permid="OzV">
            To find <m>2S</m> then we add 472 to itself a number of times.
            What number?
            We need to decide how many terms (<term>summands</term>) are in the sum.
            Since the terms form an arithmetic sequence,
            the <m>n</m>th term in the sum
            (counting <m>2</m> as the 0th term)
            can be expressed as <m>2 + 3n</m>.
            If <m>2 + 3n = 470</m> then <m>n = 156</m>.
            So <m>n</m> ranges from 0 to 156, giving 157 terms in the sum.
            This is the number of 472's in the sum for <m>2S</m>.
            Thus
            <me permid="hXn">
              2S = 157\cdot 472 = 74104
            </me>.
          </p>

          <p permid="uHe">
            It is now easy to find <m>S</m>:
            <me permid="Oew">
              S = 74104/2 = 37052
            </me>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </example>
      
      <p>
        We can find the sum of a geometric sequence using the <term>multiply, shift, and subtract</term> strategy.
    </p>

    <example permid="OVu">
        <statement>
          <p permid="hnt">
            What is <m>3 + 6 + 12 + 24 + \cdots + 12288</m>?
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution permid="msL">
          <p permid="rMy">
            Multiply each term by 2, the common ratio.
            You get <m>2S = 6 + 12 + 24 + \cdots + 24576</m>.
            Now subtract: <m>2S - S = -3 + 24576 = 24573</m>.
            Since <m>2S - S = S</m>, we have our answer.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </example>
      
      <p>
        Perhaps you've used something similar before.
    </p>
    
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <m>0.\overline{9} = 1.</m>
            </p>

        </statement>
    </example>


    
</subsubsection>


  
  
  
  
