     <backmatter>
      <index>
        <title>Index</title>
        <index-list />
      </index>
      <appendix xml:id="appendix-counting">
        <title>Counting Techniques</title>
        
        <p>
            Throughout the course, we'll collect lots of ways to count things. However, they often seem really similar to one another, so in this appendix I will try to collect various archetypal problems and methodologies.
            This will be a work in progress.
        </p>
        
        <section>
            <title>Additive and Multiplicative Principles</title>
            
            <p>
                First, recall the statements of the <xref ref="additive-principle" text="custom">Additive Principle</xref> and <xref ref="multiplicative-principle" text="custom">Multiplicative Principle</xref>.
            </p>
            
            <p>
                Both involve independent events; the difference between the two is therefore the difference between <q>or</q> and <q>and</q>.
            </p>
            
            <question>
                <title>The Additive Principle Question</title>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                    If event <m>A</m> can occur in <m>m</m> ways and event <m>B</m> occurs independently of <m>A</m> in <m>n</m> ways, how many ways can <m>A</m> or <m>B</m> occur?
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </question>

            
            <example>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Lila's Sweet Shop sells <m>m</m> types of ice cream and <m>n</m> types of frozen yogurt. There are then <m>m+n</m> ways to get a single scoop of frozen yogurt <em>or</em> ice cream (additive principle) and <m>m\cdot n</m> ways to get one scoop of frozen yogurt <em>and</em> one scoop of ice cream (multiplicative principle).
                    </p>
                </statement>
